# Style Guide: {{PROJECT_NAME}}

## General Principles

- Small files, single responsibility (aim for < 200 lines per file)
- Explicit over implicit — name things clearly, avoid clever shortcuts
- No global mutable state
- Composition over inheritance
- Handle errors explicitly — no silent failures

## Naming

- Variables/functions: `camelCase` (TS/JS) / `snake_case` (Python/Rust)
- Types/Classes: `PascalCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Files: `kebab-case.ts` / `snake_case.py`
- Boolean variables: prefix with `is`, `has`, `should`, `can`

## Functions

- One function, one purpose
- Max ~20 lines; extract if longer
- Name describes what it returns, not how it works
- Prefer pure functions (no side effects) for business logic

## Error Handling

- Never swallow errors silently
- Use typed errors / result types where the language supports it
- Log errors with enough context to debug (never log raw user data)
- Return errors to callers; don't throw across module boundaries

## Comments

- Write comments for WHY, never WHAT (the code shows what)
- A comment that re-states the code is noise — delete it
- Use TODO: for known tech debt (link to a spec or issue)

## TypeScript-Specific

- `strict: true` in tsconfig — no exceptions
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow, or proper types
- Prefer `type` over `interface` for plain shapes; use `interface` for extension points
- Explicit return types on exported functions

## Python-Specific

- Type hints everywhere (`mypy strict`)
- Prefer dataclasses / Pydantic models over plain dicts
- `from __future__ import annotations` at top of every file

## Testing

- Test file mirrors source file location
- Test name describes behavior: `it_returns_401_when_token_expired`
- One assertion concept per test (can have multiple `expect` calls for the same thing)
- No test interdependencies — each test is self-contained
